Case Study: How a Wellness Technology Company Play it Smart

SANDRA BOAKYE

2024-05-15

First Phase: Ask

Introduction and Background

This case study is about Bellabeat, a high-tech manufacturer of health-focused products for women. Bellabeat is a successful small company which have the potential to become a larger player in the global smart device market. Urška Sršen and Sando Mur founded Bellabeat and there is also the Bellabeat marketing analytics team. Products of Bellabeat includes:

  • Bellabeat app: The Bellabeat app provides users with health data related to their activity, sleep, stress, menstrual cycle, and mindfulness habits.
  • Leaf: Bellabeat’s classic wellness tracker can be worn as a bracelet, necklace, or clip. The Leaf tracker connects to the Bellabeat app to track activity, sleep, and stress.
  • Time: This wellness watch combines the timeless look of a classic timepiece with smart technology to track user activity, sleep, and stress. The Time watch connects to the Bellabeat app to provide insights into your daily wellness.
  • Spring: This is a water bottle that tracks daily water intake using smart technology to ensure that users are appropriately hydrated throughout the day. The Spring bottle connects to the Bellabeat app to track hydration levels.
  • Bellabeat membership: Bellabeat also offers a subscription-based membership program for users. Membership gives users 24/7 access to fully personalized guidance on nutrition, activity, sleep, health, beauty, and mindfulness based on their lifestyle and goals.

Business Task

To analyze smart device usage data to gain insight into how consumers use non-Bellabeat smart devices and then select one Bellabeat product to apply these insights to. * Analyze Fitbit fitness tracker data to gain insights into how consumers are using the app and discover trends for Bellabeat marketing strategy.

Key Stakeholders

  • Urška Sršen and Sando Mur

Let’s create a weight category (e.g., Underweight, Normal, Overweight)

combined_data <- combined_data %>%
  mutate(WeightCategory = case_when(
    BMI < 18.5 ~ "Underweight",
    BMI >= 18.5 & BMI < 24.9 ~ "Normal",
    BMI >= 25 & BMI < 29.9 ~ "Overweight",
    BMI >= 30 ~ "Obese"
  ))

The box plot categorizes weight and compares the distribution of activity minutes across these categories.

ggplot(combined_data, aes(x = WeightCategory, y = VeryActiveMinutes)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = "Very Active Minutes by Weight Category", x = "Weight Category", y = "Activity Minutes")

Summary statistics for Activity and Weight

summary_stats <- combined_data %>%
  summarise(
    total_ids = n_distinct(Id),
    mean_activity = mean(VeryActiveMinutes, na.rm = TRUE),
    mean_weight = mean(WeightKg, na.rm = TRUE),
    sd_activity = sd(VeryActiveMinutes, na.rm = TRUE),
    sd_weight = sd(WeightKg, na.rm = TRUE)
  )

print(summary_stats)
##   total_ids mean_activity mean_weight sd_activity sd_weight
## 1        33      23.58562     63.3196    26.07449  7.875164

Observation

  • Mean - The average amount of activity per day is approximately 23.59 minutes. This suggests that, on average, participants are engaging in relatively low levels of physical activity each day. Depending on the context this could be considered insufficient.

  • The standard deviation of 26.07 minutes is quite high relative to the mean. This indicates a wide variation in the amount of daily activity among participants. Some participants are likely engaging in much higher levels of physical activity, while others may be engaging in very little or none.

  • The fact that the standard deviation is greater than the mean suggests that the distribution of activity minutes is highly variable. This could imply that the dataset includes a mix of very active and very inactive participants, rather than a more uniform distribution of activity levels.

Interpretation

  • The high standard deviation indicates that while the average activity is low, there are participants with significantly higher and lower activity levels. This wide range can be seen as a positive sign if it includes very active individuals, but it also highlights a substantial portion of the population that may not be engaging in sufficient physical activity.

  • Given the high standard deviation, there may be outliers in the data, such as participants with exceptionally high or low activity minutes. It would be useful to examine a histogram or box plot of the activity data to visualize this distribution and identify any outliers.

  • If the data represents a broader population, the low average activity level could indicate a need for public health interventions aimed at increasing daily physical activity. This might include programs to encourage more frequent exercise or promote active lifestyles.

Recommendations

ggplot(combined_data, aes(x = VeryActiveMinutes)) +

## Observations: * The distribution is heavily right-skewed, with a large number of participants recording very few “Very Active Minutes” each day. There is a significant peak at 0 “Very Active Minutes,” indicating that many participants did not engage in any very active minutes on many days.The frequency of participants with very active minutes decreases as the number of active minutes increases. * The tail extends to the right, showing that a smaller number of participants engage in higher levels of very active minutes. There is a rapid decline in frequency as very active minutes increase. Most participants have fewer than 50 very active minutes per day. There are a few participants with very high active minutes (over 100, and even up to 200+). These outliers represent individuals with exceptionally high levels of very active minutes.

ggplot(combined_data, aes(y = VeryActiveMinutes)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = "Box Plot of Very Active Minutes", y = " Very Active Minutes")

## Observations: * The median (middle line in the box) of very active minutes is quite low, indicating that at least half of the participants have very few or no very active minutes.

*The box itself represents the interquartile range (IQR), which is the range between the first quartile (25th percentile) and the third quartile (75th percentile). The IQR is relatively small, suggesting that the majority of participants have low levels of very active minutes.

  • The whiskers extend to 1.5 times the IQR from the quartiles. In this plot, the upper whisker reaches up to about 50 minutes, indicating that most participants have very active minutes within this range.

  • There are many points above the upper whisker, indicating outliers. These outliers represent participants who have significantly more very active minutes compared to the rest of the participants. Some outliers have very active minutes exceeding 100 and even up to 200 minutes, showing a small group of highly active individuals.

Explanations:

  • The low median and small IQR indicate that most participants engage in few or no very active minutes. This aligns with the histogram’s observation of a right-skewed distribution with a high frequency of low activity levels.

  • The numerous outliers suggest a high degree of variability in the dataset. While most participants are not very active, there is a notable subset that is highly active, which significantly skews the data. The presence of these outliers contributes to the high standard deviation observed in the summary statistics.

  • The data suggests a need for initiatives to increase very active minutes among the majority of participants. Programs encouraging moderate to vigorous physical activity could help in achieving better health outcomes.

  • The outliers might represent specific groups, such as athletes or individuals with highly active lifestyles. Understanding the characteristics of these outliers could help in designing targeted interventions.

What are some trends in smart device usage?How could these trends apply to Bellabeat customers?How could these trends help influence Bellabeat marketing strategy?

  • Understanding Consumer Behavior: The analysis of daily activity and weight data helps in understanding how Bellabeat’s target audience (women using smart devices) are engaging with their health and wellness. This understanding can inform the marketing strategy by highlighting the typical activity levels and weight profiles of users, and identifying patterns or outliers.

  • Product Features and Benefits: Insights into how physical activity correlates with weight can be used to emphasize the benefits of Bellabeat’s products. For example, if the data shows that higher activity levels are associated with healthier weight profiles, marketing can highlight how Bellabeat products help users track and increase their daily activity to achieve better health outcomes.

  • Targeted Marketing Campaigns: The variability in activity levels and the potential identification of different user segments (e.g., highly active vs. less active users) can lead to more targeted marketing campaigns. Personalized messages can be crafted to address the specific needs and goals of different user groups.

High-Level Recommendations for Marketing Strategy:

*Emphasize Personalization: Data Insight: The wide range of activity levels and the mean activity being relatively low suggest that users have diverse activity habits and needs.

*Recommendation: Highlight the personalized tracking and tailored recommendations features of Bellabeat products in marketing materials. Promote how the devices can adapt to each user’s lifestyle and help them achieve their personal health goals.

Promote Health and Wellness Benefits:

  • Data Insight: Correlations between activity levels and weight can be leveraged to show tangible health benefits.

*Recommendation: Use testimonials, case studies, and data-driven content to show how increased activity tracked by Bellabeat devices has led to positive health outcomes. Create campaigns around success stories of users who have improved their health metrics using Bellabeat products.

##Segmented Marketing Campaigns: * Data Insight: The variability in activity levels indicates different segments of users.

*Recommendation: Develop marketing strategies tailored to different user segments identified through data analysis. For example, create distinct campaigns for new mothers, fitness enthusiasts, and women looking to manage stress. Each campaign can focus on the specific benefits relevant to these groups, such as sleep tracking for new mothers or stress management features for busy professionals.

Educational Content:

  • Data Insight: The standard deviation indicates a wide variation in user engagement.

  • Recommendation: Invest in educational content that helps users understand the importance of regular physical activity and how Bellabeat devices can help them track and improve their activity levels. This content can be distributed through blogs, social media, webinars, and email newsletters.

Leveraging Digital Marketing Channels:

  • Data Insight: Bellabeat already uses a variety of digital marketing channels.

  • Recommendation: Use insights from the data to create more engaging and informative content for social media, Google Search, YouTube, and display ads. Highlight data-driven results and benefits of using Bellabeat products to attract new customers and retain existing ones.

*Example Campaign Ideas: “30-Day Activity Challenge”: Encourage users to increase their daily activity with a challenge. Use data to show typical activity levels and set achievable goals. “Real Stories, Real Results”: Share real user stories and data showing the impact of Bellabeat products on their health. “Know Your Numbers”: An educational campaign explaining the importance of tracking health metrics and how Bellabeat products can help.
